# Couple Money Communication

Money conflict in relationships is often about more than math. It may involve values, fear, control, trust, responsibility, or different emotional meanings attached to money.

Common patterns in couple money conflict:
- one partner avoids while the other pushes
- one partner wants structure while the other wants flexibility
- spending triggers blame or defensiveness
- financial decisions become tied to power or safety

Healthier money conversations often include:
- speaking from personal feelings instead of accusation
- naming the goal of the conversation
- discussing one issue at a time
- staying specific instead of making global judgments
- focusing on shared stability rather than “winning”

Helpful phrases:
- “I want us to feel more secure, not criticized.”
- “Can we look at this together without blaming each other?”
- “What does spending mean to you emotionally?”
- “What would feeling safer with money look like for us?”

Supportive reminder:
A productive financial conversation usually starts when both people feel less threatened and more understood.
